		<td><b>A question about the MMC5 &amp; NES original PCM.</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />So, I've made a couple of demo PCM programs, like 7-bit 44KHz ones and MMC5 8-bit 22KHz ones. But one guy, after recording the sound from FCEUX and comparing it with a regular wav file using some software, says there seems to be some distinguishable differences.<br />Is that the emulator/recording problem, or it is my problem, or the limitation of the NES?<br />Sorry to say I know few about the software he uses, and I can only report what I know.<br /><br />(In the making of the programs, I simply converted those sound files to wav files, removed the headers, and then in the case with 7-bit PCM, right shifted every byte by one bit.)

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
